    <Descriptive_Notes>
      <Descriptive_Note>
        <Note_Text>Relatively small, rectangular dropleaf tables with a drawer or drawers below. The leaves are supported by brackets. The form was introduced during the Chippendale period and intended to serve many purposes. The name refers to the Earl of Pembroke.</Note_Text>
        <Note_Language>English</Note_Language>
        <Note_Contributors>
          <Note_Contributor>
            <Contributor_id>10000000/VP</Contributor_id>
          </Note_Contributor>
        </Note_Contributors>
        <Note_Sources>
          <Note_Source>
            <Source>
              <Source_ID>2000002851/Aronson, Encyclopedia of Furniture (1965)</Source_ID>
            </Source>
          </Note_Source>
        </Note_Sources>
      </Descriptive_Note>
      <Descriptive_Note>
        <Note_Text>Mesas con alas con un cajón o cajones debajo de la cubierta en cada extremo. Introducidas durante el período Chippendale y destinadas para servir a muchos propósitos.</Note_Text>
        <Note_Language>Spanish</Note_Language>
        <Note_Contributors>
          <Note_Contributor>
            <Contributor_id>10000131/CDBP-SNPC</Contributor_id>
          </Note_Contributor>
        </Note_Contributors>
        <Note_Sources>
          <Note_Source>
            <Source>
              <Source_ID>2000051034/TAA database (2000-)</Source_ID>
            </Source>
          </Note_Source>
        </Note_Sources>
      </Descriptive_Note>
      <Descriptive_Note>
        <Note_Text>Klaptafels met één of meerdere laden onder het tafelblad aan beide zijden. Ze werden tijdens de Chippendale-periode geïntroduceerd als geschikt voor vele doeleinden.</Note_Text>
        <Note_Language>Dutch</Note_Language>
        <Note_Contributors>
          <Note_Contributor>
            <Contributor_id>10000205/AAT-Ned</Contributor_id>
          </Note_Contributor>
        </Note_Contributors>
        <Note_Sources>
